23:57.591 --> 23:58.592
said that man. And then one of the soldiers, one of 
the assistant soldiers told the captain, don't do

23:59.032 --> 24:04.960
that. Give him a chance. Maybe he'll talk down the 
way they claimed they took him for a trial. But he

24:14.092 --> 24:17.216
didn't get over there, because they kill him for 
the reward. They sure believe in the reward.

24:19.499 --> 24:29.108
Mother said that on those days anybody do 
something, they didn't think about the life of the

24:19.499 --> 24:29.108
man, they didn't think about their personality, 
nothing. What they think is about the reward they

24:29.848 --> 24:35.934
was going to receive, no matter how they get it, but 
they get it. When did your mother and father get

24:36.134 --> 24:38.616
married? Well, they never told us nothing about 
that. We were too young, I guess, or something. We

24:47.824 --> 24:48.865
just... They never did ask, no. We were kind of... 
We never did ask, but my mother, when she passed

24:52.861 --> 24:59.251
away, she was 63 or 65 years. 63 or so, and she died in 
what year? In 1960. In 1960. So she was quite a bit

25:06.562 --> 25:10.147
younger than your father, probably. Yes, she was 
younger than my dad. She was younger, but you see,

25:12.451 --> 25:21.585
those couples in those days, they didn't have 
any... any protection like they got on these days

25:21.565 --> 25:46.915
and the family was just a what you call it they just 
come handy one baby after another that's why

25:21.565 --> 25:46.915
mother had so many babies she had seven girls and 
six girls and six boys and out of those six boys and

25:21.565 --> 25:46.915
six girls that's one boy is dead and one we still 
live in ten boys and i mean five boys and five Well,

25:47.367 --> 25:52.371
that's really remarkable for those days that all 
the children, or nearly all of them, lived. And

25:52.391 --> 25:54.433
they were healthy children. I never did remember 
that one went to the hospital or had tonsils or

25:54.533 --> 26:03.020
stomach aches. We were just raised on the farm, you 
know, like a... Who was the oldest child in your

26:03.040 --> 26:11.988
family? Well, my oldest sister, but she passed 
away. That's the one I remember her. Her name was

26:17.050 --> 26:18.817
Alec. She passed in 1935. Do you know when she was 
born? No, I don't remember. I remember one of the

26:28.593 --> 26:36.802
girls was born in 1922, and another 1923, 24, and 
25. That's me. You were born in 25. And my other

26:39.425 --> 26:41.667
little brother was born in 26. Yeah, the one that's 
a minister, he was born in 26. Yeah, every year, you

26:45.691 --> 26:58.245
see, I was born in

26:45.691 --> 26:58.245
December the 4th, 1926, while my brother was born 
in December the 2nd, 1925. 26, I was 25, and he was

26:58.681 --> 27:03.409
born in 26, just two days. And every time we get a 
birthday, we are in the same week. You see, I'm the

27:08.458 --> 27:12.245
fourth, he's the second, and I'm in the fourth. 
Almost, you know, the same. Almost the same day.

27:15.631 --> 27:16.292
The same day. Well, now, how did your father happen 
to leave Mexico? Well, he, he, he, uh, He just

27:24.736 --> 27:26.878
worked his way over here. He said because he had to 
pay $18 for each passport. And there was my mother,

27:32.703 --> 27:48.438
and my daddy, and my sister, they called him Alec, 
and Raymond, and Luis, and Eileen, and Martin, and

27:32.703 --> 27:48.438
Manuel. There was eight kids that come from 
Mexico. Now, the other ones were born over here.

27:54.267 --> 27:55.188
they were gone. And then my older sister, that's 
the one that was, that passed away, and then there

27:56.110 --> 28:03.680
was Manuel. And out of those, out of the bring from 
Mexico, we still ate. Well, you said something

28:10.149 --> 28:16.238
before about some people that wanted him to be 
abandoned with them before he came. That was my

28:16.258 --> 28:18.021
father-in-law. Your father-in-law? Oh, I 
thought that was your father. No, my father, well,

28:21.105 --> 28:22.587
my father, My father did say something about that, 
too, because he said that people, after the

28:22.837 --> 28:36.249
revolution, after they got through fighting and 
everything come to normal, they didn't want to

28:22.837 --> 28:36.249
work. Steel didn't want to work. They wanted to 
steal and rob the other poor people. And they were

28:40.853 --> 28:44.076
close to the soldiers, because they know how to 
shoot. And my daddy, sometimes, he said, well,

28:44.957 --> 28:52.624
that's one of the reasons I come to the United 
States, because I was tired of the life they were

28:44.957 --> 28:52.624
living, just sleeping on the rocks and shooting at 
each other just like an animal. Let's put it that

28:58.142 --> 28:59.223
way. We didn't even know when we were going to eat. 
Sometimes we don't eat all day. We don't drink no

29:07.451 --> 29:08.592
water. We have nothing. We just have to stay there. 
Then my father said, I thought about it. If I got out

29:15.819 --> 29:19.422
of the service, I'll come to the United States And 
he was living in Piedras Negras, and then he moved

29:19.604 --> 29:26.531
to Eagle Pass. When did he leave Mosques and come to 
Piedras Negras? I think in 1925

29:29.573 --> 29:35.859
that I was born. Right, the year you were born, he 
moved to the border. To the border, close to the

29:38.242 --> 29:47.130
border, because he said he was a... My daddy thinks 
a lot of, what you call it, shepherds. He believes a

29:47.650 --> 29:51.615
lot on those things because he was a milkman.

29:53.558 --> 29:58.384
Before he entered the service and after he got out 
of the service, he was a milkman. He had some little

29:58.404 --> 30:05.193
goats and he delivered some milk. And he still 
thinks that when he goes back, he will do that same

30:05.893 --> 30:10.680
thing. He was a kind of shepherd. He always lived in 
the woods or whatever you call it. He believes a lot

30:15.967 --> 30:20.534
in those things. And then he said he sell wood. And 
then he started thinking he ought to give his

30:25.001 --> 30:29.227
family a chance. He didn't want them to live like he 
did. And you know those Rocky Mountains and they

30:33.314 --> 30:37.660
were no school or nothing. But still my daddy had a 
good school. My grandma believes a lot in school

30:41.532 --> 30:45.197
and they sent him to school. They sent him to school 
in Moskos before the revolution. They had a good

30:48.963 --> 30:50.164
school. And I had an uncle, I remember him as 
Gregori. He had a good school. He was a good, well I

30:55.552 --> 31:01.921
say good sport because he knew boxing and all that. 
You know, they teach the boys all that and he was a

31:02.462 --> 31:06.628
good, and then I remember my uncle coming to visit 
us or to stay with us in 1932. And he asked my daddy,

31:14.526 --> 31:20.192
well, what are you going to do with all this bunch of 
kids you've got and they know how to read and write?

31:20.312 --> 31:21.473
My daddy said, well, I have to work. I ain't got no 
time to deal with the kids. He said, well, you give

31:24.036 --> 31:25.517
them to me. He went and got those pencils. I think 
you remember they were kind of a, well, I don't

31:29.942 --> 31:33.966
know. They would make a little piece of wood, and 
they had a little leg. He bought a lot of them and

31:40.118 --> 31:44.145
started teaching us. I knew how to read and write in 
Spanish when I was seven years old. And this was

31:50.216 --> 31:53.321
your uncle who was living with you right then? And 
he taught you how to read and write in Spanish? To

31:55.845 --> 31:57.388
all the family. We didn't go to school, you know, to 
public school until I was 10 years old, 1935. I was

32:03.855 --> 32:06.558
10 years old. How many years did you go then? I went 
about five years. But you'd had schooling in

32:10.141 --> 32:12.464
Spanish before that. Yeah. Do you think that 
helped you learn English? Well, in a way, yes. In a

32:17.108 --> 32:26.818
way, I say yes, but you see, it was a little harder 
for me because I had a little mixed up there because

32:17.108 --> 32:26.818
I thought the same thing in Spanish was in English. 
until I had to forget my Spanish and start in my

32:27.085 --> 32:30.289
English. And it was, I tell the kids, I don't 
suggest for nobody to know Spanish and then start

32:30.309 --> 32:40.803
in English, because it's kind of a little hard 
until you have to forget your Spanish and then

32:30.309 --> 32:40.803
start in English. It's the same thing backwards. 
If you know English first, it's hard to learn

32:42.325 --> 32:49.214
Spanish. But, oh, I don't think I asked you, what 
town did you live in or near in the Brazos Valley?

32:55.722 --> 32:56.503
Well, Brian. It was right outside of Brian. Yeah. 
Well, what you call the brass bottom, they call

33:00.028 --> 33:04.714
here Mumford. The steel store, that's where I went 
to school. Steel store and Mumford. Mumford.

33:08.899 --> 33:09.280
Mumford. Both schools I attended. How did you 
happen to come, or how did your father happen to

33:10.962 --> 33:17.130
come here to Brian instead of staying on the 
border? Let me see.

33:20.895 --> 33:23.839
They said that we had an uncle before that. before 
my dad, that he was already living here close to

33:24.022 --> 33:29.030
Hearn in a farm. They call it Valley Johnson or 
Goodland. They call it that farm. It's a big

33:36.141 --> 33:38.004
plantation center. They call it Goodland. Well, 
he happened to live there. So he said, I'm going to

33:42.111 --> 33:45.276
send for my brother. They got a lot of kids to come 
over here, and he can live here like a king. And I

33:50.504 --> 33:51.025
think The way it looks, I think my uncle sent him 
some money because he had to pay $18. For each one?

33:57.488 --> 33:59.831
Each one, you know, to make the passport. And we all 
got passports, and they cost $18 each one. And some

34:04.798 --> 34:10.025
money to pay that station wagon that bought us. 
Now, the station wagon in those days was what you

34:10.386 --> 34:14.271
call it? It was just first class, like you come in a 
greyhound. And my daddy said that. That man bought

34:20.873 --> 34:22.976
also over there. And I guess my uncle paid him and 
everything. So we settled right there in that

34:27.823 --> 34:31.027
place. And I can remember the cotton. It must be, I 
don't know what, it was on August. And I guess it was

34:40.721 --> 34:45.808
close to, you know, the cotton was about that big or 
something like that. Because I can remember, you

34:45.828 --> 34:49.733
know, we still remember the farms and and a tree 
that was there and everything. Your father was

34:53.227 --> 34:58.474
actually working on the land that was owned by 
somebody else. And then we moved to there. We moved

35:00.556 --> 35:03.300
to this other place they called Scott. It's close 
to this other side of the heart. And then we moved to

35:08.726 --> 35:13.392
Mumford with this. This man that owns these 
things, the seals, the seals own this place. And

35:18.536 --> 35:23.721
then we owned with this man that he called himself 
Bullet. But before that, those men, I know them.

35:27.805 --> 35:32.129
But further down, I don't remember who was our 
bosses or nothing. But I remember this one's over

35:32.169 --> 35:33.730
here. And then we lived with the Escamados over 
here in the bottom. The same Escamado, he was our

35:37.554 --> 35:39.315
boss. And then we moved to another place they call 
This, let's see, I don't remember the name.

35:50.502 --> 35:52.965
Anyway, Ward, his name was Ward. He owns a huge land 
from this river to the other river. But what

35:58.972 --> 36:03.398
happened, he was not married man. He didn't have no 
family. So we lived there. And that's where we went

36:07.083 --> 36:09.205
to school, to steel store. We were staying in that 
place with that man. He had a lot of farm, a lot of

36:11.729 --> 36:13.551
farm. Well, when did your father and the rest of 
your family move to Oklahoma? They moved in 1943.

36:18.846 --> 36:20.608
In 1943. Why did they move to Oklahoma? Well, you 
see, the beginning of the deal was this.

36:30.901 --> 36:32.744
We were living in Wheelock. Well, you see, the 
crops over there was not so good. So somebody that

36:36.549 --> 36:42.677
went over there by the name of Martinez called, My 
daddy said, if you want to bring a bunch of people to

36:42.927 --> 36:51.081
pull some cotton, pick some cotton, we got a good 
place over here. So we took a trip and we thought it

36:51.361 --> 36:54.327
was good. And it was good and we thought it was the 
Holy Land because everything over there was

36:54.387 --> 37:01.619
going, you know, good. The cotton, they paid good 
money and everything. And still they pay good

37:04.882 --> 37:08.587
money over there in the state of Oklahoma. That's 
the reason my daddy's black over there. And so the

37:10.791 --> 37:17.080
boys did too, you know, because they don't work in 
the cities, you know, they work on the farms. They

37:17.140 --> 37:17.881
like to... They still work on the farms. On the 
farms. And they thought the, you know, the job was

37:20.545 --> 37:29.839
easier and better than here in Texas. So they 
still, they were there. That's their reason

37:32.202 --> 37:34.686
because they said they think they... crops was 
better over there because they got an irrigation.

37:40.749 --> 37:43.973
They make them good. Well did you all travel around 
much when you were kids and pick crops or did you

37:43.993 --> 37:50.380
just mostly stay in the Razzus Valley and pick? No, 
we traveled a lot. We went to the state of Arkansas

37:52.002 --> 37:57.028
and we went to Tennessee. Memphis, Tennessee. We 
went over there to Arkansas and the state of

37:58.810 --> 38:05.559
Louisiana and the state of Oklahoma and the state 
of Texas. Yeah, we traveled. What was that like?

38:07.542 --> 38:10.125
Did you enjoy it or did you dread it? How did you feel 
about it? Well, I'll put it this way. I didn't like

38:13.730 --> 38:25.125
it, but you see, as a family kid, I have to tango 
along with them, but I didn't like it because I

38:13.730 --> 38:25.125
thought it was not good to be sleeping on the truck 
all the time and sleeping on it just like a tramp.

38:25.493 --> 38:27.776
But I'll give you a thought about that. I said, 
well, maybe when I get married, I'll settle down

38:27.836 --> 38:30.861
and don't do this. But find out that I got married, 
my husband started traveling. I said, well, you

38:34.566 --> 38:37.570
better go yourself because I'm not going. But it 
was a lot of fun, all right? You know, when you

38:40.995 --> 38:43.419
forget about everything. It was a lot of fun when 
you go with a lot of girls and boys in the truck and

38:43.439 --> 38:51.951
just yell and jump off the truck and pull all day, 
pull cotton. We thought it was fun. we got to be, you

38:53.708 --> 38:56.573
know, well, we thought it was good. But then, now 
that I, I don't think I ever want to repeat it again.

39:01.862 --> 39:08.372
So there were things about it that were really very 
good and fun and good memories and things that you

39:01.862 --> 39:08.372
just wouldn't have to live through again. No, I 
tell my husband, I say, if you want to go, you know,

39:08.432 --> 39:16.065
places where you better go yourself. This trip 
they took to Mexico. I say, I like to go there, I say,

39:18.189 --> 39:20.172
but not Not that much, I said, because I got what you 
call arthritis. And, you know, it's sitting on

39:25.291 --> 39:29.637
your legs, on your feet, on your body. I said, for 
arthritis, it's not good. You have to move,

39:31.640 --> 39:33.903
exercise. He said, well, I stay with the kids. You 
better go and enjoy yourself. Well, you have been

39:38.268 --> 39:39.991
to Mexico, though. Yeah, I like it over there. I do. 
But I didn't have no vacation. They have. Where do

39:44.975 --> 39:46.537
you work? I work at the cashmere hatchery. 
Cashmere hatchery at the hatchery. Oh, with the

39:52.444 --> 39:54.406
baby chickens. Yeah, what do you do? Well, the 
first step we do is to set the eggs for the, what you

39:55.428 --> 40:02.616
call it, for the hatch. And then wait for the babies 
to hatch. And then, you know, we got what you call a

40:07.582 --> 40:12.849
setting every Monday and every Thursday. Every 
Monday and every Thursday. and we have to pick them

40:14.287 --> 40:20.436
out of the trays, count them, and then take to this 
other place. Some sectors, they take the little

40:20.917 --> 40:32.975
rooster and the little pullet, and then all the 
pullets are in different boxes, and all the

40:20.917 --> 40:32.975
roosters are in different boxes, and we have to 
keep up with all those things. Can you really

40:33.456 --> 40:35.519
separate them when they're that young? Yes, 
because we got one... one kind of chickens that you

40:41.303 --> 40:47.211
can tell which is which just by the wings. Oh, 
that's an improvement over when I was growing up

40:47.691 --> 40:53.859
and we just had to get the little chickens and wait 
until they got big enough. Yeah, well, but this

40:54.059 --> 41:02.190
kind of flock that our bosses are raising is 
different from the others. You see, if you just get

41:02.590 --> 41:10.821
the little wing and open the little wing and it's 
made like a little fan. as a little puller. And if

41:12.560 --> 41:22.250
you get another one and don't have any things like a 
little fin or little white feathers, that's a

41:12.560 --> 41:22.250
rooster. Well, now that's something I didn't know 
about yet. That's fascinating. That's

41:25.534 --> 41:26.395
interesting. It sure is. It's interesting. And I 
wish more people would learn that, because they

41:27.676 --> 41:34.704
pay you good money if you don't have to separate it. 
And we got some sections, they call us, some

41:35.144 --> 41:40.470
doctors from college. They can do that, but not all 
the people. But they put it to us where we can do it.

41:48.233 --> 42:03.314
Now it's got so easy that even us, we can get a box and 
just pick a little chicken and just open the little

41:48.233 --> 42:03.314
feather, I mean the little wing, and you can tell. 
Well, now how many children do you have? I was a

42:07.179 --> 42:08.601
mother of nine. Nine? Nine, but I raised five. I 
lost four little boys. When they were babies? Yes,

42:17.681 --> 42:21.005
they were babies. My first baby was a little boy, 
and he died before he was born. Then I had a little

42:27.555 --> 42:31.360
girl, and she didn't die. And then I had another 
little boy, and he died. He was born at 2 o'clock,

42:34.164 --> 42:38.250
and he died at 9 o'clock. And then I had another set 
of twins, twin little boys, and they died because

42:38.753 --> 42:47.503
they were born as a premature baby. So they were too 
little, I said too little. And then I had another

42:51.047 --> 42:53.990
little girl, she didn't die. And then I had another 
one that didn't die, another one that didn't die,

42:54.010 --> 43:00.998
and the little boy. and another little girl, and I 
have five. They have one son that lives? Yeah, just

43:05.372 --> 43:06.473
one. How old are your children now? Well, my oldest 
girl, she's 27, and the other one is 22, and the

43:08.115 --> 43:19.966
other one, she'll be 21, and my boy will be 17, and my 
little girl will be 15. I've got a 14-year-old.

43:24.931 --> 43:27.854
Well, what are your children doing now? Well, my 
girls, my... My oldest girl, she's working at the

43:31.707 --> 43:37.614
couch cafeteria at the bus station. She works 
there. And my other girl, she lives in the state of

43:39.236 --> 43:41.980
Oklahoma. She works in a factory. I guess it's made 
by the government. I guess she's sewing or

43:46.185 --> 43:47.627
something. Are either one of them married? Yeah, 
both are married. Oh, they're both married. And

43:51.472 --> 43:53.935
the other one is working at the Coca-Cola. And my 
boy, he's in high school. And my little girl is in

43:56.178 --> 43:58.761
junior high. Did your children graduate from high 
school? Yes, two of them. The other one got to the

44:03.734 --> 44:06.198
11th grade. And this is the one that is home. He's 
handsome. This is the one that was talking to you a

44:11.245 --> 44:14.249
while ago. And then my boy, he's in the 10th grade. 
Yeah, he said he's going to finish. He's just two

44:19.556 --> 44:22.040
more years. I got hopes that the other two will 
graduate out of the five. They saw the two graduate

44:28.492 --> 44:35.364
where I had four graduates and just one of the girls 
there when she was 17. But she passed to the 11th

44:36.266 --> 44:41.235
grade, but she didn't make it. Well, it sounds like 
from what you're saying, going all the way back to

44:41.255 --> 44:49.189
your grandmother, that education was important 
in your family. Oh, yes. Do you know when they came

44:51.560 --> 44:55.827
into the Muscus, I can't say it, area? Do you know 
when your family originally came to Northern

44:55.867 --> 44:59.473
Mexico? No, from over there? From further south? 
No, I really don't know, but my mother was born in

45:05.103 --> 45:09.851
Monclova. In Monclova. She told me that she was 
married in Monclova, and I think that the That was

45:16.248 --> 45:17.769
your mother or your grandmother? No, my mother. 
Your mother was born in Mancova. But my

45:20.512 --> 45:26.757
grandmother, my daddy, they were originally from 
Musquis. The way they looked, the way they talked,

45:27.118 --> 45:31.882
they lived there all the time. Maybe in their 
little ranch or village or something, but the main

45:32.202 --> 45:40.970
town was Musquis because all the papers are there 
from Musquis. They don't call it Coahuila. They

45:42.591 --> 45:44.533
call it Coahuila. I was just wondering, Coahuila 
was settled in the 1600s. It was a long time ago.

45:56.174 --> 46:01.603
When my son-in-law told me that he was going to take 
me to my hometown. Have you been back to your

46:01.643 --> 46:02.925
hometown? No, I haven't. Because, I don't know, 
when we went to Mexico, we went to Laredo. But he

46:09.438 --> 46:14.857
said, this time, all the time we go, we're going to 
go through Iklupes, Piedras Negras, and then

46:09.438 --> 46:14.857
Musques. He said, it's a beautiful town. I said, 
well, maybe I'm planning to. I'm looking forward

46:19.314 --> 46:20.578
to it.

